import React from "react";
import styled from "styled-components";

const Wrapper = styled.section`
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  background: url(../images/background.jpg);
  background-position: center center;
  background-size: cover;
  height: 100vh;
  width: 100%;
  .hero-inner {
    display: grid;
    gap: 15%;
    padding: 5%;
    h1 {
      color: #318379;
      line-height: 30px;
      @media(min-width: 568px){
        width: 70%;
      }
    }
    a {
      color: #318379;
      text-decoration: none;
      &:hover{
        text-decoration: underline;
        color: #4ce;
      }
    }
  }
`;

function Hero() {
  return (
    <Wrapper>
      <div className="hero-inner">
        <h1>Welcome to Wallasteve Auto & Mechanical Engineering</h1>
        <p>Title: Enhancing University Experience through a Mobile Application: A Case Study

Introduction

Background: The increasing reliance on mobile technology and the growing need for efficient communication and access to information have prompted universities to develop mobile applications to enhance the overall university experience.
Objective: This case study aims to explore the development and implementation of a comprehensive mobile application for a hypothetical university, focusing on its features, benefits, challenges, and impact on students, faculty, and staff.
Context and Scope

Description of the University: Provide an overview of the university, including its size, academic programs, campus facilities, and existing technological infrastructure.
Mobile Application Objectives: Define the primary goals of the mobile application, such as improving communication, enhancing access to resources, streamlining administrative processes, and fostering student engagement.
Development Process

Stakeholder Engagement: Describe the involvement of key stakeholders, including university administrators, IT department, faculty members, students, and support staff, in the development process.
Requirements Gathering: Explain the methods used to gather requirements, such as surveys, focus groups, and interviews, to ensure the application meets the needs and expectations of the university community.
Design and Prototyping: Discuss the iterative design process, wireframing, and prototyping stages, highlighting the user-centered approach and the incorporation of feedback from stakeholders.
Development Tools and Technologies: Provide an overview of the software development tools, technologies, and platforms utilized to build the mobile application, considering factors like cross-platform compatibility, security, and scalability.
Key Features and Functionalities

User Authentication and Profile Management: Explain the login and registration process, user profile management, and integration with existing university systems for seamless user experience.
Course Management: Describe features that enable students to view their course schedules, access lecture materials, submit assignments, and receive notifications about class updates.
Campus Navigation: Highlight the interactive campus map, building locator, and GPS-based navigation system to help students navigate the university campus efficiently.
Library Resources: Discuss features that allow students to search the library catalog, reserve books, access e-books and scholarly databases, and receive due date reminders.
Event Calendar: Explain the event management system, which provides information about academic, cultural, and extracurricular activities happening on campus, along with the ability to RSVP and receive event reminders.
News and Announcements: Detail the functionality that delivers university news, announcements, and updates to users in real-time.
Student Support Services: Describe features that facilitate access to counseling services, academic advising, career guidance, and other support systems.
Feedback and Surveys: Highlight the mechanisms for students and faculty to provide feedback, participate in surveys, and report issues or concerns.
Implementation Challenges

Technical Challenges: Discuss the technical hurdles faced during the development and integration of the mobile application with existing university systems, ensuring data security and maintaining performance.
User Adoption and Training: Address the challenges associated with user adoption, training, and change management, including strategies employed to encourage widespread acceptance and usage.
Maintenance and Updates: Explain the measures taken to ensure the application remains up-to-date, secure, and compatible with evolving mobile operating systems and devices.
Impact and Benefits

Student Engagement and Satisfaction: Discuss how the mobile application has improved student engagement, satisfaction, and overall university experience, providing real-life examples and feedback from students.
Efficiency and Productivity: Highlight how the application has streamlined administrative processes, reduced paperwork, and enhanced operational efficiency for faculty and staff.
Communication and Collaboration: Explore how the mobile application has improved communication and collaboration among students, faculty, and staff, fostering a sense of community and facilitating knowledge sharing.
Data Analytics and Insights: Explain how the application's data analytics capabilities have provided valuable insights into user behavior, preferences, and areas for improvement.
Conclusion

Summary: Recap the key points discussed in the case study, emphasizing the successful development and implementation of the university mobile application.
Lessons Learned: Highlight the lessons learned from the project, including best practices, areas for improvement, and recommendations for future mobile application initiatives.
Future Enhancements: Discuss potential future enhancements and features that can be added to the mobile application to further improve the university experience.
Note: This case study is based on a hypothetical university mobile application implementation. The specifics of the case study can be tailored to a real-world university's context and requirements.</p>
        <a href="#">Learn more</a>

      </div>
    </Wrapper>
  );
}

export default Hero;
